In your code the thread can leave that infinite `for(;;)` loop only in one way - after it fulfills condition from the `if(p == head &amp;&amp; tryAcquire(arg))` - because it&#39;s the only `return` statement, you also don&#39;t have any breaks.

However, you said that &quot;lock is not obtained&quot;, which means the Thread has to continue execution of what is in this for loop, which means executing second if (that suspends thread again). 

When you have a construct
```java
try {
  // some code
}finally{
 // finally execution
}
```
The code in the `finally` block will execute only after the execution leaves `try` block (either normally or due to exception).

